Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


2026-04-16 12:11:10 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Power supply module internal wiring between battery + and LED/output node'] hypothesis_explanation='The new battery is confirmed good at 12 V, but both PSU output cables and the LED‑resistor junction sit at ~0.012 V above battery − instead of near 12 V. Continuity tests show low resistance paths from the battery to both output cables, yet in operation the outputs remain at ground potential and the LED branch never sees the battery voltage. The LED and its resistor themselves test nominal; the anomaly is that the node that should be the positive rail (feeding the LED branch and the external + output) is effectively shorted or tied to battery − inside the PSU module. This internal miswiring/short collapses the supply so that the rest of the chain and all indicators receive 0 V. Therefore the remaining fault is a wiring/connection error inside the power supply module that connects the intended + output/LED node directly (or via a very low‑impedance path) to battery −, preventing any voltage from appearing at the outputs or across the PSU LED. Repair requires opening the PSU module and correcting this internal positive‑rail misconnection/short.'
